Loan Repayment Challenge¶

Objective¶

Predict the loan risk or loan quality (loan repayment)

2.1 Check if funded or non-funded loan is taken into account of the loan risk?

In [8]:

In [9]:
funded_loan = data[data["isFunded"].eq(1)]

g = sns.FacetGrid(funded_loan, col="isFunded", height=5, aspect=1.5)
g.map(sns.histplot, "loanStatus")
g.add_legend()
g.set_xticklabels(rotation=75)
plt.show()

Seems like the non-funded loan at the upper plot is being withdrawn the most and rejected appear to be somewhat lesser, while most of the funded loan at the bottom plot is being paid off.

The loan application is withdrawn due to many vague reasons and it may not impact directly to the loan risk itself, so that's no point getting this large set of withdrawn loan and fit into the model. So we're going to drop the non-funded loan and we will only retained the funded loan in this case.

3. Feature Engineering¶

In this step, we will perform and handle labelling, missing values, encoding and feature transformation.

3.1 Identify Label/Target Feature (y)

In this case, we will use loanStatus as our target feature, y.

To define a loan as risky or non-risky, we simply consider that:

Loan Risk Class Characteristics Loan Status Types
non-risky 0 the loan is being paid off Settlement Paid Off, Paid Off Loan
risky 1 the loan is being defaulted, charged off, rejected or in the status of bankruptcy Charged Off, Settled Bankruptcy, Rejected
In [13]:
category = {
    "Settlement Paid Off": 0,
    "Paid Off Loan": 0,
    "Charged Off": 1,
    "Settled Bankruptcy": 1,
    # "Rejected": 1,
}

data["risk"] = data["loanStatus"].map(category)
data.dropna(subset=["risk"], how="all", inplace=True)
data["risk"] = data["risk"].astype(int)

97.38% non-risky loan, 2.62% risky loan

This is an imbalanced dataset, where there's a huge difference between risky loan and non-risky loan class. There are several ways to mitigate the model biases towards the majority class, but in this case, we will use F1-Score as our model performance metrics because for accuracy performance metrics might just predict 97.38% of the non-risky loan class but the risky loan might all get wrong.

There's a loan processing period that might be a useful features for the model, because if the loan process time is long, the loan might be risky.

Through these plot, we can see that:

  1. The loans that are originated at Monday and Friday are at high risk (First Plot)
  2. The loans that are accepted at Saturday are at high risk (First Plot)
  3. The loans that are originated and accepted under the same day are at high risk (Second Plot)
  4. The loans that are originated and accepted at night are mostly at high risk (Third Plot)

4.2 Handling Highly Correlated Features

We will drop the highly correlated features using pearson correlation technique because there's no point using two features that are almost related.

In [34]:

In [35]:
# get highly correlated columns
def correlation(dataset, threshold=0.95):
	col_corr = set()
	corr_matrix = dataset.corr()
	for i in range(len(corr_matrix.columns)):
		for j in range(i):
			if abs(corr_matrix.iloc[i, j]) > threshold:
				colname = corr_matrix.columns[i]
				col_corr.add(colname)
	return col_corr


high_corr_columns = correlation(features, 0.95)
high_corr_columns

5.6 Model Experiment

We will use f1 score as our performance evaluation metrics mainly for imbalanced dataset.

We will compare the two datasets(balanced/imbalanced) above in this model experiment using 3 types of algorithm/model:

  1. Logistic Regression - Since we are dealing with binary classification problem, we are going to use this as our first experiment.

  2. Decision Tree - Since we are dealing with high-skewed data and outliers, let's have a try on this with un-normalized and normalized data.

  3. Neural Network - Since I love neural net, surely I have to try this.

5.6.1 Logistic Regression

In [56]:
def model():
    input = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(train_features.shape[-1]))
    x = tf.keras.layers.Dense(16, activation="relu")(input)
    x = tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation="relu")(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.Dense(2, activation="relu")(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
    output = tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)

    model = tf.keras.Model(input, output)

    model.compile(
        loss=tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(),
        optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.01),
        metrics=METRICS
    )
    return model

def predict(model, X):
    y_pred = model.predict(X).squeeze()
    y_pred = tf.where(y_pred > 0.5, 1, 0)
    y_pred = y_pred.numpy()
    return y_pred

Conclusion¶

  1. Only approximately 2.62% of risky loan that leads to imbalance dataset.
  2. More data about risky loan need to be collected to ensure that the model created is able to predict properly in the real world situation.
  3. There's still quite vague and difficult to determine the feature importance
  4. More effort need to be done on feature understanding, feature engineering and feature selection to extract and introduce more features based on the context of finance.
  5. More modelling experiment including hyperparameter tuning (e.g. GridSearchCV) need to be done.
